WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Good morning, Jacob. It's Tuesday, April seventh, twenty twenty-six. It's

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
eighty-three degrees in Jefferson City again — warm and sunny,

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
southwest winds five to nine miles per hour. Over in

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Tacoma, Katelyn's got a cooler day — fifty-nine, cloudy early,

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
clearing up in the afternoon. Today is one of those

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
days where local and global collide in a way that

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
feels almost absurd. You're voting on a half-cent sales tax

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
for road maintenance in Cole County while the president threatens

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
to destroy every bridge and power plant in Iran by

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
midnight. "Infrastructure Day," he's calling it. Let's start with the

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
big picture. Trump's deadline hits tonight at eight P-M Eastern,

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
seven P-M your time. Axios A-M's Mike Allen, drawing on

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
six officials with direct knowledge, paints a picture of a

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
president who is personally the most hawkish figure in his

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
own administration. One official called him "the most bloodthirsty, like

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
a mad dog," saying Hegseth and Rubio "sound like the

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
doves compared to the president." Trump has been asking advisers:

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
"What do you think of Infrastructure Day?" — framing the

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
destruction of Iranian civilian infrastructure as a branded event. Both

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
the U-S and Iran rejected a ten-point ceasefire plan brokered

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
by Pakistan. Iran wants a permanent end to the war,

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
not a temporary pause. The U-S called it "not good

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
enough" but "a significant step." Mediators are redrafting. This is

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
the fourth time Trump has set and delayed a deadline

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
— March twenty-first, March twenty-third, April sixth, and now tonight.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
The Atlantic's David Graham has the sharpest analysis: "When Trump

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
feels cornered, he lashes out most fiercely." And right now,

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
with military options narrowing and the Hormuz chokepoint giving Iran

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
leverage that bombing won't remove, Trump is very much cornered.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Meanwhile, J-D Vance is in Budapest trying to save Viktor

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Orbán, who's trailing in polls ahead of Sunday's election. The

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
irony of an American vice president flying to Europe to

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
prop up an authoritarian ally while the president threatens to

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
bomb civilian infrastructure overseas is... something. On to Artemis Two.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
The flyby is complete. The crew reached two hundred fifty-two

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.000
thousand, seven hundred fifty-six miles from Earth — four thousand,

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
one hundred eleven miles beyond Apollo thirteen's record. They're heading

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
home now. Splashdown is Friday, April tenth, off San Diego.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
The highlight was the crater naming ceremony. Commander Reid Wiseman

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
proposed two names: "Integrity," after their spacecraft, and "Carroll," after

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
his wife, who died of cancer in twenty-twenty at forty-six.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
The crew embraced each other in lunar orbit. They also

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
witnessed a solar eclipse nearly an hour long from the

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
far side of the Moon. Victor Glover on the broadcast:

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
"Earthshine is very distinct, and it creates quite an impressive

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
visual illusion." Now for the A-I news, which is extraordinary

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
today. Anthropic's revenue has tripled to a thirty billion dollar

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
run rate, up from nine billion at the end of

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
twenty twenty-five. Bloomberg reports over a thousand business customers spending

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
a million dollars or more annually. They've also sealed a

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
massive compute deal — three and a half gigawatts of

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
Google T-P-U capacity through Broadcom, coming online in twenty twenty-seven.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
An October I-P-O at roughly three hundred eighty billion dollar

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
valuation is under evaluation. This is Anthropic becoming, arguably, the

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
highest-revenue A-I company on Earth. But the biggest A-I story

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
might be the New Yorker. Ronan Farrow and Andrew Marantz

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
published an eighteen-month investigation titled "Can Sam Altman Be Trusted?"

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
It's devastating. They found Altman lobbied against the same regulations

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
he publicly advocated for, pursued billions from Gulf autocracies, and

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
tried to hide a post-firing investigation that produced no written

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
report. Former chief scientist Ilya Sutskever's memos list "lying" as

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
the first item under "Sam exhibits a consistent pattern of."

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Dario Amodei wrote in private notes: "The problem with OpenAI

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
is Sam himself." This got thirty-one thousand upvotes on Reddit.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
Meanwhile, on Good Friday, Open-A-I dumped three major leadership departures:

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
C-O-O Brad Lightcap to "special projects," C-M-O Kate Rouch stepping

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
down for breast cancer recovery, and C-E-O of A-G-I Development

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Fidji Simo on medical leave for a neuroimmune condition. The

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
organizational dysfunction narrative at Open-A-I is becoming hard to ignore.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Boris Charny, creator of Claude Code, acknowledged on Hacker News

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
that task performance degradation since February was real — not

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
just user settings. He identified "a flaw in the adaptive

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
thinking feature." A-M-D's A-I director separately called Claude Code "dumber

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
and lazier since the last update." In Apple news, the

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
iPhone Fold has entered trial production — this is real.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
Samsung display panels, book-fold design, aimed at twenty twenty-six launch.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Mac Mini and Mac Studio are facing extreme shipping delays

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
due to a severe RAM shortage. And N-A-S-A shared photos

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
shot on iPhone seventeen Pro Max during Artemis Two —

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
literally from lunar orbit. You can't buy that kind of

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
product placement. Locally, today is Proposition A. The half-cent capital

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
improvement sales tax has been in place since the nineteen

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
eighties. This is a ten-year renewal for roads, bridges, and

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
county facility maintenance. Polls close at seven P-M. Go vote.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
There was a false active shooter alert at Lincoln University

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
last night — text went out, all clear within thirty

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
minutes. Scary but resolved. U-S fifty bridge ramps remain closed

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
through April twelfth. A few quick hits. Michigan won the

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
N-C-double-A men's basketball championship last night, sixty-nine to sixty-three over

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
U-Conn. First title since nineteen eighty-nine. The Haberman and Swan

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
book is announced — "Regime Change: Inside the Imperial Presidency

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.000
of Donald Trump." June twenty-third. Gold cover. About a thousand

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
interviews. And your Rocket Mortgage statement is ready for review.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
One personal note: Katelyn texted last night about your July

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
visit. "Maybe July? We could do a little bit on

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
the island and a little in Victoria?" She's thinking about

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
trip logistics — whale watching as a "risk and expensive

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
option," camping weather concerns. Worth responding to when you get

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
a chance. Ben sent you a late-night Reddit link from

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
the Presidents subreddit. Classic Ben. That's your Tuesday. On one

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
screen, you're walking into a Cole County polling place to

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
vote on road maintenance. On the other, the president is

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
branding the destruction of a nation's civilian infrastructure like a

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
product launch. In between, four astronauts are coasting home from

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
the moon, having named a crater after a dead woman

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
they loved. The Anthropic revenue number is staggering, and the

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
New Yorker's Altman investigation is the kind of reporting that

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
changes narratives permanently. Go vote. Watch the deadline. Tell Katelyn

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.400
about the island. Your briefing, delivered.
